			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2011</a> paper:</span><br><i>Join Token-Based Event Handling: A Comprehensive Framework for Game Programming</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/TaketoshiNishimori.html">Taketoshi Nishimori</a>, <a href="../profile/YasushiKuno.html">Yasushi Kuno</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_7">10.1007/978-3-642-28830-2_7</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It proposes a coordination framework for composing event-handling behaviors in games.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagL">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> The join-token mechanism is an execution/runtime model for dispatching and synchronizing events.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3f.html"><span class="tagL">T3F: API</span></a><ul><li> The contribution is presented as a framework/API intended to be used by game programmers.
</li></ul></li></ul>
